  "title": "Classroom Game",
  "difficulty": "Moderate",
  "question_text": "<div class=\"paragraph\">Suppose Darius is creating a game for his math class final project. To play the game, a player will roll two standard number cubes and move along the game board. The game includes a rule that states, \"If you roll doubles, you go back to the starting position.\"</div><div class=\"paragraph\">Let <span class=\"tex2jax_process\">$D$</span> represent the number of rolls until the first player has to go back to the starting position. </div><div class=\"paragraph\">The random variable <span class=\"tex2jax_process\">$D$</span> has a geometric distribution with mean <span class=\"tex2jax_process\">$6$</span>. Interpret the value of the mean in the context of this problem.</div>",
  "image_files": [],
  "choices": [
    {
      "letter": "A",
      "text": "The players are guaranteed to have\n6\ndoubles rolled per game."
    },
    {
      "letter": "B",
      "text": "The first set of doubles rolled will be on the sixth roll."
    },
    {
      "letter": "C",
      "text": "Since the probability of rolling doubles is\n1\n6\n, in repeated sampling, the player should expect to roll doubles about\n1\n6\nof the time."
    },
    {
      "letter": "D",
      "text": "In repeated playing of the game, the players should expect approximately\n6\ndoubles rolled per game."
    },
    {
      "letter": "E",
      "text": "In repeated sampling of the game, the expected number of rolls it will take until a player rolls doubles is approximately\n6\n."
    }
  ],
  "correct_answer": "<strong>Choice 'E'</strong> is the correct answer",
