</span></span><span class=\"mjx-line\" style=\"border-bottom: 1.3px solid; top: -0.284em; width: 0.935em;\"></span></span><span class=\"mjx-vsize\" style=\"height: 2.711em; vertical-align: -1.344em;\"></span></span><span id=\"MJXc-Node-68339\" class=\"mjx-mo MJXc-space3\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.058em; padding-bottom: 0.332em;\">=</span></span><span id=\"MJXc-Node-68340\" class=\"mjx-mn MJXc-space3\"><span class=\"mjx-char MJXc-TeX-main-R\" style=\"padding-top: 0.387em; padding-bottom: 0.387em;\">6</span></span></span></span><span class=\"MJX_Assistive_MathML MJX_Assistive_MathML_Block\" role=\"presentation\"><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\" display=\"block\"><msub><mi>μ</mi><mi>x</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>6</mn></mfrac></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>6</mn></math></span></span></span><script type=\"math/tex; mode=display\" id=\"MathJax-Element-13616\">\\mu_x = \\frac{1}{\\frac{1}{6}} = 6</script></div>\n\nTo interpret this value, the <strong>mean</strong> of a geometric random variable is defined as <em>the expected number of trials to get the first success</em>. \n\n<strong>Choice 'E'</strong> is correct. ",
